{
  "texts": [
    "To see part (ii), it is sufficient to argue that there exist finitely many Nash equilibria.",
    "Suppose that",
    "and given that 1 is not an eigenvalue of dφ (which holds generically), we have that det(dφ ′) ̸ = 0, and hence φ ′ is a local diffeomorphism by the inverse function theorem, implying that φ ′ is bijective over B ϵ (x L, x R).",
    "This prevents another point",
    ", in other words, it bars the existence of another fixed point in the open-neighborhood of (x L, x R))."
  ]
}